text: You are wise to say so. There are too few who appreciate the importance of the research I do here.
Perhaps you are right, %PCName. The resources of your Guild would truly further my research. I shall sign up next time I travel through Balmora.
It is true, I deserve better than this rat-infested outpost. And they call this a reward for my loyal service...
My powers are indeed great, %PCName. Tell me... more about myself.
You do right to honor the ancestors.

You thinking about looking around for Dwemer sites? Well, it's your funeral. There's a well-known one called Mzahnch, on an island a ways east of Vivec. You don't look ready for that kind of excitement, but, heck, you don't try, you'll never learn, right?

Consider yourself fortunate to tread the Land of Ash. These 'High' Elves and treehuggers are a pale and mongrel breed, tainted and lessened by their long association with the beast races. The Dunmer have remained true to their heritage, and retain the handsome features of the ancient Aldmer.
I must tell you, all this self-righteous Western clamor against slavery is really tiresome. Our right to own slaves is protected by law -- IMPERIAL law. People who free slaves are breaking the law.

I must tell you, all this self-righteous Western clamor against slavery is really tiresome. Our right to own slaves is protected by law -- IMPERIAL law. People who free slaves are breaking the law. That's why Orvas Dren is hiring bounty hunters to track down these catmen and pondscum. Teach them a lesson.

This isn't the nation my ancestors founded, I tell you. Upstanding Dunmer like Orvas Dren are getting their throats slit in their beds, while that swine Hlaalu Helseth talks as if he will surrender our ancient right to have slaves. Mark my words outlander - when this Emperor dies, his legions are going to be recalled from our lands. And then we'll see who really runs Morrowind.

So, you think House Hlaalu is just an Imperial puppet? Shows what you know. Who really runs House Hlaalu? Not the house council. Those posers do what Orvas Dren tells them. Orvas Dren is the Camonna Tong kingpin. And one day, when the time is right, Orvas Dren, the Camonna Tong, and all right-thinking Dunmer will rise up, murder you outlanders in your beds, and restore Morrowind to its ancient glory.
It's not just the blight storms that are bad this year. They got all sorts of blighted beasts coming down from the mountain. It's pretty dangerous on the trails and in the outback villages.

I've heard rumours of merchants and pilgrims attacked on trails by crazed Dunmer with clubs. Not Ashlanders, mind - but dressed ragged and spouting gibberish all the same. The strangest thing is they don't take gold or goods, so they can't be bandits.

The blight storms have been so bad around Red Mountain this year that the crops and herds of the outlying villages are really suffering. The price of everything is going to go up. There's no easy cure, even for a Temple, and all they've got in the backcountry is the odd healer and pilgrim shrine.
I'm %Rank rank in %Faction, and I'd think twice about going down in a Daedric ruin without a crateful of potions and scrolls.

You like to poke your nose into doors out in the backcountry? A little suggestion. The places that look like they're made of a golden metal? With spires and towers? Those are Dwarven ruins. They're kinda dangerous -- partly because of the old Dwarven machines in them, and partly because of the kind of things that like to hide out in such old ruins. All the old ruins inside the Ghostfence, for example, are ancient Dwarven ruins. And I hear that vampires like them, too.

Our plantations depend on slaves, mostly down south in Dres District, but here in the Ascadian Isles, too. It's our right to have slaves, by law and custom, and we'll fight for it on the Council till it makes good business sense to do otherwise.
Personally, I don't want slaves. No one I know has any. But it's our right to have slaves, by law and custom, and you outlanders must learn to respect the traditions of our people.

These outlanders won't be happy until slavery is outlawed. I don't know what I'd do without slaves. Hire some shiftless, untrustworthy, evil-smelling pauper? It's our right to have slaves, by law and custom, and it's none of their damn business.

If the Great Houses want a Dunmer noble dead badly enough, they'll get a contract through the Morag Tong. If the f'lah is smart, they flee the city; go underground and lay low for a spell. But some of the braver ones wait in ambush. They rarely survive.

You're an outlander, maybe you don't know about the kinds of Daedric ruins we have here in Morrowind. Daedra cults worship the Bad Daedra. You can learn more about that at the Temple. Anyway, long ago, before the Temple put a stop to it, people used to worship bad Daedra -- Molag Bal, Malacath, Sheogorath, and Mehrunes Dagon -- at Daedra shrines. But lately, since the Empire came in, some people have taken up worshipping the bad Daedra at these old sites. And I warn you. These are dangerous places.

What are the most dangerous places in Morrowind? Well, probably the ash vampire citadels inside the Ghost Fence, on Red Mountain. But outside the Ghostfence? I guess the Daedric ruins would be the worst. They're all over the place, and full of bad Daedra, and the crazy folks who summon them. I hear vampires are pretty bad, too, but I've never seen any, personally. And the Dwemer sites are pretty bad, too.

How do you recognize a Daedric shrine? Well, they've got long, funny names, like Ashurnibibi or Zaintiraris. Some are well-known sites, like Ald Sotha and Bal Fell. And stone and architecture is unmistakable. Big, dark, grey-green stone ruins, funny angles, funny markings and patterns on the stone. Weird oval crooked doors. And inside, all funny angles.

Have you heard about poor Ienas Sarandas? He lost his patrimony betting on the guar. Sold every piece of the family silverware to pay his debts. A pity. I think it's driven him a bit mad. Wears clothes fit for a lord, and hasn't got a drake for a meal.

Don't carry those cheap armorer's hammers around with you. Hammers are dead weight. Buy them, and use them on the spot. If you're a shortblade specialist, and you like to travel light, it's often cheaper to own and carry backup weapons.

Having served with the legions for many years, and having carried the Emperor's standard, I'd like to say he was universally loved and respected. But here in Vvardenfell, the Dunmer fight each other more than the Empire, and they all blame us when they do. That's what happens when you try to bring law and justice to Elves.

These Bosmer and Khajiit don't understand the nature or value of wealth.They are certainly not loyal to the Emperor - but then no one is these days. It's not like it was when I first signed up for the Legions, let me tell you.

Every warrior worth his salt wants a suit of Ebony mail. We call it 'Godsblood' for good reason - you'll be defended as if the Three, bless their names, were watching over you. Of course, they say Daedric plate is even tougher - but evil spirits are trapped inside the metal during forging, and I want no part of that.

Every warrior worth his salt wants a suit of Ebony mail. The locals call it 'Godsblood' for good reason - you'll be defended as if the Divines themselves were watching over you. Of course, they say Daedric plate is even tougher - but evil spirits are trapped inside the metal during forging, and I want no part of that.

Always carry a jug of sujamma with you. That burst of strength, and the ability to penetrate armor and deal serious damage, will give you the one-time punch to face an opponent you normally can't handle.

Remember: there's always a welcome for you in the Imperial cult. If you're having a hard time here in Morrowind, outlander, come home to the Imperial cult shrine. We'll find a use for you, and help you feel good while doing good.

We welcome all races within the Imperial Cult. But most Dunmer natives cling to their worship of the Temple. I suppose they are more comfortable with Gods who can be seen, and speak to them in person. But Gods who take human form must also take on human imperfections. The Divines have no such flaws.
The Fighters Guild is a brotherhood of warriors. We provide a mercenary service to Morrowind, lending steel and shield to those who need our help. For the right price.

We are an Imperial Guild, serving the Emporer's law. Our members must have a clean criminal record. No contract will be accepted when it is offending the laws and customs of the realm. That means the contracts we can and can't take here can be very different than those we recieve in Cyrodiil.

Conjuration magic can be very useful for a warrior. No, I don't mean summoning monsters to fight your battles for you. But calling a Daedric weapon to your side gives you a powerful edge over your opponent. Few are lucky enough to own the genuine article - they're in the hands of wealthy collecters rather than adventurers these days.

Keep your weapons sharp, your armor in good shape. If you can't afford to have others do it, learn to do it yourself. Get the best quality you can afford. You can be no better than the quality of your tools.
Don't be in such a hurry when you're traveling. Take your time. Keep your eyes open. Learn from your experiences. You're on the road to learn about yourself and the world around you.
We turn to the ancestors for guidance. We honor them, and try to live with the wisdom that they whisper to us.

The dead who guard our Ancestral Tombs are not the product of necromancy. They rise from love of kin or faith to duty, and so are not unholy. It is but the answering of the ancestors, the awakening of those who never sleep.

Here in Morrowind, we torch Conjurers and Necromancers right up on poles where they belong. Of course, now, the Telvanni wizards, they're different - like the Altmeri sorcerors, private in their towers and private in their affairs. Don't know much about them, and don't want to.
There is no surer sign of decay in a land than to see the rites of religion held in contempt.
Everybody can learn a few spells. You don't need to be a wizard to cast spells. It makes life easier. And when you learn a spell, practice. It's the only way to learn, and it helps to pass the time.

There have been only a few rare incidents of the Mages Guild actually becoming involved in local political struggles. On these occasions, the Guild's participation has been the ultimate decider in the conflict.

If you want to trap a soul, summon the beast yourself, or purchase a scroll from someone who can. That way you make sure you are properly prepared and can defeat the creature on your own terms. Soultrapping down in Daedric Ruins is brave, but reckless, and likely to get you killed.

Before the Guild came here, magic was the preserve of the few. All the Houses had their mages, of course, and villages might have had a hedgewizard or two. But nothing respectable. Conjurers and warlocks were branded necromancers - hunted down and burnt at the stake by the Temple.
Necromancy is inherently dangerous. A mage cannot 'dabble' in it. The simplest spell requires the spilling of blood, and immediately begins to corrupt the caster's soul.

Ranis Athrys had something against wizards who aren't in the guild. It's no a surprise really - her parents were murdered by the old Telvanni Archmagister, the one before Gothren. I guess one of them caught up with her in the end.
Ranis Athrys has something against wizards who aren't in the guild. It's no a surprise really - her parents were murdered by the old Telvanni Archmagister, the one before Gothren.
Never take a life carelessly. It cheapens you, and diminishes you. Take life seriously, if taking life is your profession.
Death smiles at us all. All a man can do is smile back.
Death smiles at us all. All a mer can do is smile back.
Friends and wealth do not hold much joy for me. Yet the thrill of the chase, the grace of the kill; these are things that can still move me to laughter or tears.
Do not fear the darkness; but welcome its embrace.
The Great Houses are in a state of silent, shadowed war, of secret poisons, artful daggers and sleeping men strangled in their beds.

I shouldn't be saying this too loud, so listen close. No one LIKES Archmagister Gothren. But no one gets to vote for Telvanni archmagister, either. The Telvanni Archmagister only changes when someone kills the old archmagister. There's no one in a position to challenge him now. And Gothren has spies in every city that make sure no one starts plotting against him.

Argonians generally make for better slaves than the Khajiit. They have natural resistances to disease and poison, meaning you can work them harder, longer and in more dangerous conditions without losing your property.

Always pull a catman's lips back and check the teeth before you make a purchase. If they're black, that usually means the beast is addicted to moonsugar. Don't let the slavemasters flog you an addict slave - not at full price, anyway.

House Telvanni used to rely on Redoran mercenaries for protection and security. Now the Vvardenfell Mage-Lords are expanding their territory, we've been forced to turn to Western mercenaries for guards and agents. That's the reason you see so many outlanders swelling our ranks for the moment.

House Telvanni used to rely on Redoran mercenaries for protection and security. Now the Vvardenfell Mage-Lords are expanding their territory, they're turning to Western mercenaries for guards and agents. Lucky for us, eh %PCName?

Archmagister Gothren doesn't live in Sadrith Mora. That might seem unusual for the head of the House, but when you think of all the scheming wizards and assassins for hire in the city, you see it's a precaution. A more isolated tower is a more secure tower, and far easier to defend.
It is safer to be feared than loved, if you cannot be both.
If you're having trouble persuading someone, offer a bribe. Don't be so stuffy. Bribes are the lubricant of honest commerce.
A wealthy mer can afford anything except a conscience.

In the conservative south, the Indoril parties and the Temple still have a lot of influence in the Councils, but up north, Imperial influence is strong, and Hlaalu family and retainers control most of the wealth and political power. Of course, within their own territories, each of the five Great Houses rule their local councils - but the power of Hlaalu and Imperial coin is very influential.
Every mer has his price, %PCName. Even friendship is for sale.
The earth of Vvardenfell is rich with veins of ebony and diamond. Fame and fortune would be piled upon the lucky f'lah who discovered fresh deposits for their House.

The nobles of House Hlaalu are great merchant princes. A wealthy individual has already proven their worth by turning fortune into profit. But they are also mer of means - able to invest in and expand the clan, with great resources at their disposal.

We've cast our lot with the Empire. Our fortunes will wax and wane with theirs. The Telvanni, on the other hand, have simply ignored Imperial law to secure their position. I'm talking about these rogue settlements, where mages disguised as pilgrims are dropped by caravans all over the Ashlands.
If you help someone, they'll remember. If you're loyal to others, they'll be loyal to you. Do the right thing. You know the right thing. Do the right thing, so you'll never regret what you've done.

The glory of the Indoril is long in the past. They once used their control of the Tribunal priesthood to dominate the other Houses, but their hegemony was overthrown during the Armistice, never to recover.
I have never seen Vivec myself, but I have felt his presence. I know that he loves his people and protects us. He is no far-away idea like these uncaring Imperial gods, but flesh and blood.
Death comes for us all, in the end. Sadly, we cannot choose how, but we can decide how we meet that end; and so the manner in which we are remembered.
Do not laugh at serious matters, for it shows disrespect. Do not spread rumors, for they fester and will in turn be spread about you.

Did you hear Bolvyn Venim killed another outlander in a duel? The man was an officer in the House Guard, but Bolvyn Venim insulted his ancestors at a meal, so of course the officer had to demand satisfaction. And of course he had no chance against Venim. He may be lacking in honour - but certainly not courage.

They say they don't have much of a problem here with vampires. From my experience, that's the truth in the settled parts of Vvardenfell. But in the backcountry, you hear rumors. Out near Dagon Fel, Maar Gan, Molag Mar, you hear people talk of running into vampires in Dwemer ruins, and in ancestral tombs. Best to be careful. You don't want to run into those babies. And if you do, you want a nice, crisp copy of Divine Intervention so you can get safe, fast, all in one piece.
Vampires are not as much of a problem here as back in the West. Here, the Dark Elves burned them out centuries ago, and the Temple makes sure they don't come back.
Lately the Ordinators have been taking verbal shots at the Legion guards. The Legion brass has got a muzzle on the troops, but they don't like it one bit.
It's bad enough with the blight storms this year, but the Ashlanders are also going crazy, jumping caravans and pilgrims, raiding villages. They ought to send the Legions out and teach them a lesson.

Have you heard of this new secret cult, the Sixth House? They say they sit around in caves, cutting off pieces of their own flesh and eating it. It's that corprus disease -- makes the flesh grow wild and crazy. Cut a piece off, and another piece grows back, bigger and better. Guards say, 'We're looking into it.' Right. That makes me feel better.
Now that Dagoth Ur has fallen, perhaps the Temple will dismantle the Ghostfence, and let our ancestors who fuel it finally rest in peace.
The last Buoyant Armiger assault against Red Mountain ended in defeat. They retreated and most survived, but since then we've relied on the Ghostfence to keep Dagoth Ur and his hordes at bay.

If you're thinking of traveling up country, near Sheogorad, or out Molag Amur way, or inside the Ghostfence, you need to know about corprus. It's a disease that turns normal creatures into beasts. Turns men into twisted, mad lumps of flesh, superhumanly strong, and full of hatred. You get corprus from fighting with diseased creatures. It's hard to get corprus, but harder to get rid of it. In fact, I hear there is no cure.

The Great Houses tend to favour certain races as mercenaries. House Hlaalu employs the brute muscle of Nords and Orcs. The Redoran admire the skill and discipline of the Redguard. Even the reclusive Telvanni have many Altmer and Bosmer in their pay.
Buy from merchants and traders who like you. You get better prices. Members of your own factions usually like you best.

Be careful before you get into bed with a particular faction. There is usually a competitor or ideological opposite to any one House or Guild - so find out who your new enemies will be before you pledge your allegiance.

Red Mountain dominates the minds and spirits of Dunmer. It looms high above the horizon in all northern settlements. It is sacred, and a site of pilgrimages - that is, folk travel to shrines on its remote flanks, but the Ghostfence prevents any travel to the peak and crater themselves.
Khajiit respect men and mer, but we do not wish to be compared to you. Calling a Khajiit, even an Ohmes-Khajiit, 'bald' or 'unclawed,' is a deadly insult.

Veneration of the Eight Divines and Tiberius Imperator has gained some local acceptance, particularly among House Hlaalu, but the Tribunal Temple is and always has been the one and only state religion of Morrowind.

We don't much love foreigners here in Vvardenfell, and we don't thank you for interfering. A people should keep to their own, if you take my meaning. And that's not the Empire's way. I look around, I don't see much benefit from uniting the provinces, unless you're a fatcat merchant, or maybe a soldier.
If someone attacks you first, you have the right to defend yourself. If someone DOESN'T attack you first, you're going to break the law if you attack him.
Do you remember that old saying from Black Marsh, %PCName? That the best soil for a seed is found in your heart.
There is an old saying from Black Marsh, outlander. That the best soil for a seed is found in your heart.

Some Daedra, like Gods to the other cultures, are sacred to the Dunmer. They even consider Boethiah as the first of their kind. I'll grant that, to strangers, it may seem odd that the Dunmer hold the darker powers in esteem. Rest assured though; there is more to Morrowind than just a heathen den of demon-worshippers.

The Houses play out what we Dunmer call the 'Great Game'. The Morag Tong is a tool in the hands of the Great Houses, in the unending competition for honor, glory and power. According to the Mephala Entente, anyone may be marked, from the High Hlaalu himself to the lowliest Telvanni serf. Non-Dunmer are forbidden to hire or to be marked; some say that Tiber Septim himself negotiated this arrangement with the Morag Tong at the time of the Armistice.

The Empire has conquered through power, armies and strength. Yet what they build in peace, they draw from Altmer ideas, civilisation and intellect. Even the common tongue of the Empire, Tamrielic, is based on our speech and writing. And it is a poor imitation, if I may say so.

Some Redorans think they know better than the Emperor what's right and wrong, if you take my meaning. And I've heard it said that the Hlaalu adopted Imperial culture, but I've never seen such a lazy, selfish, backstabbing lot in my life. As for the Telvanni, well, they're wizards - and I don't like wizards.

'Dar' in a Khajiti name means 'thief,' but this should not alarm you. 'Dar' is like the Nordic 'Clever Hudvar' or the Breton 'Arnand the Fox.' A Khajiit with 'Dar' in his name is clever, and maybe clever with his hands, but not always a thief by odd Imperial property customs.
In Skyrim, it is an old tradition to rub canis root on the trees surrounding your house as a ward against werebears.

Iron and steel are easy to repair. Just heat them up and pound them back into shape. You can even use a camp fire in a pinch. Ebony can only be hammered when heated. It develops small cracks that eventually shatter the material if hammered cold. Now I hear Daedric should always be worked on at night... ideally under a new or full moon, and never during an eclipse. A red harvest moon is supposed to be best.

Many Redguards serve as mercenaries in House Redoran. It's not just that we make talented swordsmen, but we share a similar outlook on life. The rocky deserts of Hammerfell are tough and unforgiving, much like the Ashlands where the Redoran make their home. So we understand that life is hard-fought, and hard-earned.

We Bosmer have long been misunderstood as outcasts. It stems from the 'Green Pact' we make with our God - in part of which we promise to eat the meat of our fallen foes. This disgusts other races, and so they call us cannibals and savages. They do not understand that this is how we show respect for nature, and the body of the enemy - wasting neither meat, nor bone, nor fur.

Not only can a nimble acrobat leap to places others cannot, they also have a better sense of balance and control. When you can climb the steep slopes, you'll uncover the secrets hidden across the mountains in Vvardenfell.
Take care when using Telvanni bugmusk, or any other magic that makes you more charming. No one likes being used, and your new friend will realise they've been tricked after that sweet haze wears off.
Take care when using Telvanni bugmusk, or any other magic that makes you more charming. No one likes being used, and your new friend will realise they've been tricked after that sweet haze wears off.

Casting a fireball might look flashy, but it's a foolish Mage who relies upon it here. Use your head, outlander. You're in Morrowind. Our homeland. We shrug off the heat. Folks say it comes from years of living under the sweltering shadow of Red Mountain.

Casting a fireball might look flashy, but it's a foolish Mage who relies upon it here. Use your head, %PCRace. You're in Morrowind. Land of the Dunmer. And Dunmer are naturally resistant to heat. Catch my drift?
Any hedge wizard can burn up his enemies with fire. Yet destroying your enemy so directly should be the last resort of a skilled battlemage.

There's no harm in sleeping rough, and eating what you can find. Living off the land. Anywhere outside of town you can just lay down under the stars and take your rest -- provided there aren't any thieves or kagouti around.

Wielding a mace is all about timing and momentum. Once the swing of the mace has begun, stopping it or slowing it down is difficult. The fighter commits not just to the blow, but also the recoil. Begin your strike when the opponent is leaning forward, hopefully off balance. It is completely predictable that he will lean backward, so aim for a point behind his head. By the time the mace gets there, his head will be in it's path.

Every creature, living or dead, is powered by a soul. Without it, they are just lumps of flesh or piles of bones. This animating force can be contained within a soul gem, if the soul gem has the capacity. From the gem, the power can be used to power magical items.

Every creature, living or dead, is powered by a soul. Without it, they are just lumps of flesh or piles of bones. This animating force can be contained within a soul gem, if the soul gem has the capacity. From the gem, the power can be used to power magical items.

The key to unarmed combat is concentration. All of the blow is concentrateded into a small point. Therefore it is more potent. To strike with just the thumb can be more deadly that to strike with the whole fist. However, only the highly trained fighter can do this.

Even if you were born common, you can attempt to conduct yourself like gentry. Learn the law and local customs. If you don't mind your manners, you'll get called out to a duel.

You'll need plenty of levitation potions if you want to do business with House Telvanni. You can brew your own from the trama root, racer plumes, or coda flowers. A thick, bitter-tasting root of the trama shrub grows in the Ashlands, Molag Amur, and Red Mountain regions. Racer plumes are plucked from dead cliff racers. Coda flowers are collected from the draggle-tail plant which blooms in swampland.

Levitation potions can be produced from the trama root, racer plumes, and coda flowers. A thick, bitter-tasting root of the trama shrub grows in the Ashlands, Molag Amur, and Red Mountain regions. Racer plumes are plucked from dead cliff racers. Coda flowers are collected from the draggle-tail plant which blooms in swampland.

To cure common diseases, combine gravedust and green lichen. Gravedust is spirit-affinitive dust taken from remains buried in consecrated ground. Green lichen is a hardy primitive plant that grows on the rocks around the West Gash.
Stay away from the mudcrabs. Swamp Fever starts with a slight temperature, but you'll be raving and delirious by the end. Go join the Tribunal Temple. Initiates get free Cure Disease at the shrines.

Take care around sickened creatures. The bite of a diseased Alit or Kagouti is unusually vicious, and their frenzied brains cannot feel pain. Even if the beast is dead, the disease lingers upon the carcass. Many hunters come to me for healing after they strip meat and hides from sick beasts.

Invisibility is one of the most prized of all potions. They can be made only from crushed diamonds and bittergreen petals. Diamonds are expensive, and Bittergreen only flowers around Red Mountain, where few dare to travel.

Wortcraft is what we call eating raw magical ingrediants. When you grind herbs and roots against the teeth, it occasionally releases its simplest essence and results in a fleeting effect on the eater.

Common thieves will stick a dagger in an opponent's back. This may slay the target, but more often gives him time to scream and drenches the attacker with blood. Not good. A throat-slash, properly executed, can both slay and silence a guard, while leaving your clothes unstained.
There is a profit to be made from death. Not only can you rob the deceased, but, if your victim has enemies, which rich people often do, you can be paid even more for it.

The blight storms have been so bad around Red Mountain this year that my crops and herds are really suffering. I'm going to have to put my prices up, and the product I'll be selling will taste more like ash than last seasons.

You did not just defeat Dagoth Ur, my friend. You healed the very land we depend on. Since the ash has stopped raining from Red Mountain, our fields have been blooming like never before. The harvest will be plentiful this year, and my crops will taste cleaner and sweeter than I or my ancestors can ever remember.
While silver weapons are slightly less durable than steel, they have the unique ability to wound ghosts and Daedric monsters.
The primitive burial customs of the Dunmer are nothing but foolish superstitions. Only we hold sway over life and death.

Casting Alteration spells is convincing a greater power that it will be easier to change reality than to resist the push of your command. Reality is like wind and water. It cannot be removed. But it can be bent, channeled, or redirected.

The trickiest of all armours to repair is Glass. Hammer blows struck across the grain run the risk of shattering the armor. Same goes with weapon blows. So make sure you always carry your own hammers if you protect yourself with Glass.

Warhammers and Battle Axes may feel slow to swing, but they're deadly in the hands of a trained fighter. The heavier your weapon, the more it will literally club down your opponent, causing them to stagger, and interrupting their own attacks.

We don't tolerate necromancers here, outlander. They steal the bones of our fathers and treasure from our tombs. The wise spirits of our ancestors are forced into their service like slaves and beasts. That's why the Temple hunts them down and burns them at the stake.

Some rough customers come into town now and then for supplies. I reckon they're smugglers and bandits holed up in the caves and mines herebouts. Me, I'm no fighter, I just keep my head down. But an adventurer like yourself could go and clean them out. Might make yourself some gold while you're at it.
Find out where the Camonna Tong drink around town. Then stay away from those places. They don't like outlanders, except under building foundations.

You look like a f'lah who knows his way around, eh? Looking for what others are looking for. Well, they don't have an Imperial charter, but there's honor among thieves, if you know what I mean. Look in the tradehouses and cornerclubs, talk around. If you look likely, and talk likely, they'll give you the word.

The Thieves Guild and the Camonna Tong are in a Guild War for control of Vvardenfell. The Camonna Tong are the ancient Dunmer syndicate. They hate outlanders, and always will. If they win, there'll be no place for you here, outlander.
Stay clear of the Camonna Tong. They don't like outlanders, and what they don't like, they kill.
